# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hume-rothery-rules
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] An **alloy** is a mixture of chemical elements of which in most cases at least one is a metallic element, although it is also sometimes used for mixtures of elements; herein only **metallic alloys** are described.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Metallic alloys often have properties that differ from those of the pure elements from which they are made.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The vast majority of metals used for commercial purposes are alloyed to improve their properties or behavior, such as increased strength, hardness or corrosion resistance.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Metals may also be alloyed to reduce their overall cost, for instance alloys of gold and copper.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In an alloy, the atoms are joined by metallic bonding rather than by covalent bonds typically found in chemical compounds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The alloy constituents are usually measured by mass percentage for practical applications, and in atomic fraction for basic science studies.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Alloys are usually classified as substitutional or interstitial alloys, depending on the atomic arrangement that forms the alloy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] They can be further classified as homogeneous (consisting of a single phase), or heterogeneous (consisting of two or more phases) or intermetallic.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] An alloy may be a solid solution of metal elements (a single phase, where all metallic grains (crystals) are of the same composition) or a mixture of metallic phases (two or more solutions, forming a microstructure of different crystals within the metal).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Examples of alloys include red gold (gold and copper), white gold (gold and silver), sterling silver (silver and copper), steel or silicon steel (iron with non-metallic carbon or silicon respectively), solder, brass, pewter, duralumin, bronze, and amalgams.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Alloys are used in a wide variety of applications, from the steel alloys used in everything from buildings to automobiles to surgical tools, to exotic titanium alloys used in the aerospace industry, to beryllium-copper alloys for non-sparking tools.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] An alloy is a mixture of chemical elements which forms an impure substance (admixture) that retains the characteristics of a metal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Alloys are made by mixing two or more elements, at least one of which is a metal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] This is usually called the primary metal or the base metal, and the name of this metal may also be the name of the alloy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The other constituents may or may not be metals but, when mixed with the molten base, they will be soluble and dissolve into the mixture.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The mechanical properties of alloys will often be quite different from those of its individual constituents.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] A metal that is normally very soft (malleable), such as aluminium, can be altered by alloying it with another soft metal, such as copper.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Although both metals are very soft and ductile, the resulting aluminium–copper alloy will have much greater strength.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Adding a small amount of non-metallic carbon to iron trades its great ductility for the greater strength of an alloy called steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Due to its very-high strength, but still substantial toughness, and its ability to be greatly altered by heat treatment, steel is one of the most useful and common alloys in modern use.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] By adding chromium to steel, its resistance to corrosion can be enhanced, creating stainless steel, while adding silicon will alter its electrical characteristics, producing silicon steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Like oil and water, a molten metal may not always be miscible with another element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] For example, lithium, magnesium, or silver are almost completely insoluble with pure iron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Even when the constituents are soluble, each will usually have a saturation point, beyond which no more of the constituent can be added.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Iron, for example, can stably hold a maximum of 6.67% carbon, forming a compound called cementite.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Although the elements of an alloy usually must be soluble in the liquid state, they may not always be soluble in the solid state.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] If the metals remain soluble when solid, the alloy forms a solid solution, becoming a homogeneous structure consisting of identical crystals, called a phase.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] If as the mixture cools the constituents become insoluble, they may separate to form two or more different types of crystals, creating a heterogeneous microstructure of different phases, some with more of one constituent than the other.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, in other alloys, the insoluble elements may not separate until after crystallization occurs.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] If cooled very quickly, they first crystallize as a homogeneous phase, but they are supersaturated with the secondary constituents.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] As time passes, the atoms of these supersaturated alloys can separate from the crystal lattice, becoming more stable, and forming a second phase that serves to reinforce the crystals internally.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Some alloys, such as electrum—an alloy of silver and gold—occur naturally.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Meteorites are sometimes made of naturally occurring alloys of iron and nickel, but are not native to the Earth.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] One of the first alloys made by humans was bronze, which is a mixture of the metals tin and copper.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Bronze was an extremely useful alloy to the ancients, because it is much stronger and harder than either of its components.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, in ancient times, it could only be created as an accidental byproduct from the heating of iron ore in fires (smelting) during the manufacture of iron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Other ancient alloys include pewter, brass, and pig iron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In the modern age, steel can be created in many forms.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Carbon steel can be made by varying only the carbon content, producing soft alloys like mild steel or hard alloys like spring steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Alloy steels can be made by adding other elements, such as chromium, molybdenum, vanadium, or nickel, resulting in alloys such as high-speed steel or tool steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Small amounts of manganese are usually alloyed with most modern steels because of its ability to remove unwanted impurities, like phosphorus, sulfur, and oxygen, which can have detrimental effects on the alloy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, most alloys were not created until the 1900s, such as various aluminium, titanium, nickel, and magnesium alloys.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Some modern superalloys, such as incoloy, inconel, and hastelloy, may consist of a multitude of different elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] An alloy is technically an impure metal, but when referring to alloys, the term *impurities* usually denotes undesirable elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Such impurities are introduced from the base metals and alloying elements, but are removed during processing.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] For instance, sulfur is a common impurity in steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Sulfur combines readily with iron to form iron sulfide, which is very brittle, creating weak spots in the steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Lithium, sodium and calcium are common impurities in aluminium alloys, which can have adverse effects on the structural integrity of castings.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Conversely, otherwise pure-metals that contain unwanted impurities are often called "impure metals" and are not usually referred to as alloys.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Impure metals such as cast iron or wrought iron are less controlled, but are often considered useful.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Oxygen, present in the air, readily combines with most metals to form metal oxides, especially at higher temperatures encountered during alloying.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Depending on the alloy, this can eventually result in a failure of the component being produced.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Great care is often taken during the alloying process to remove excess impurities, using fluxes, chemical additives, or other methods of extractive metallurgy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Alloying a metal is done by combining it with one or more other elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The most common and oldest alloying process is performed by heating the base metal beyond its melting point and then dissolving the solutes into the molten liquid, which may be possible even if the melting point of the solute is far greater than that of the base.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] For example, in its liquid state, titanium is a very strong solvent capable of dissolving most metals and elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In addition, it readily absorbs gases like oxygen and burns in the presence of nitrogen.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] This increases the chance of contamination from any contacting surface, and so must be melted in vacuum induction-heating and special, water-cooled, copper crucibles.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Carbon has a very high melting-point and only does so under high atmospheric pressure, so it was impossible for ancient civilizations to combine with iron as a liquid solute.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] It may also be done with one, more, or all of the constituents in the solid state, such as found in ancient methods of pattern welding (solid-solid), shear steel (solid-solid), or crucible steel production (solid-liquid), mixing the elements via solid-state diffusion.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] By adding another element to a metal, differences in the size of the atoms create internal stresses in the lattice of the metallic crystals; stresses that often enhance its properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] For example, the combination of carbon with wrought iron produces steel, which is stronger than iron, its primary element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The electrical and thermal conductivity of alloys is usually lower than that of the pure metals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The physical properties, such as density, reactivity, Young's modulus of an alloy may not differ greatly from those of its base element, but engineering properties such as tensile strength, ductility, and shear strength may be substantially different from those of the constituent materials.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] This is sometimes a result of the sizes of the atoms in the alloy, because larger atoms exert a compressive force on neighboring atoms, and smaller atoms exert a tensile force on their neighbors, helping the alloy resist deformation.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Sometimes alloys may exhibit marked differences in behavior even when small amounts of one element are present.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] For example, impurities in semiconducting ferromagnetic alloys lead to different properties, as first predicted by White, Hogan, Suhl, Tian Abrie and Nakamura.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Unlike pure metals, most alloys do not have a single melting point, but a melting range during which the material is a mixture of solid and liquid phases (a slush).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The temperature at which melting begins is called the solidus, and the temperature when melting is just complete is called the liquidus.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] For many alloys there is a particular alloy proportion (in some cases more than one), called either a eutectic mixture or a peritectic composition, which gives the alloy a unique and low melting point, and no liquid/solid slush transition.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Alloying elements are added to a base metal, to induce hardness, toughness, ductility, or other desired properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Many metals and alloys can be work hardened by creating defects in their crystal structure.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] These defects are created during plastic deformation by hammering, bending, extruding, et cetera, and are permanent unless the metal is recrystallized.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Otherwise, some alloys can also have their properties altered by heat treatment.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Nearly all metals can be softened by annealing, which recrystallizes the alloy and repairs the defects, but not as many can be hardened by controlled heating and cooling.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Many alloys of aluminium, copper, magnesium, titanium, and nickel can be strengthened to some degree by some method of heat treatment, but few respond to this to the same degree as does steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The base metal iron of the iron-carbon alloy known as steel, undergoes a change in the arrangement (allotropy) of the atoms of its crystal matrix at a certain temperature (usually 820 °C (1,500 °F) or more, depending on carbon content).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] This allows the smaller carbon atoms to enter the interstices of the iron crystal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] When this diffusion happens, the carbon atoms are said to be in *solution* in the iron, forming a particular single, homogeneous, crystalline phase called austenite.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] If the steel is cooled slowly, the carbon can diffuse out of the iron and it will gradually revert to its low temperature allotrope.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] During slow cooling, the carbon atoms will no longer be as soluble with the iron, and will be forced to precipitate out of solution, nucleating into a more concentrated form of iron carbide (Fe3C) in the spaces between the pure iron crystals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The steel then becomes heterogeneous, as it is formed of two phases, the iron-carbon phase called cementite (or carbide), and pure iron ferrite.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Such a heat treatment produces a steel that is rather soft.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] If the steel is cooled quickly, however, the carbon atoms will not have time to diffuse and precipitate out as carbide, but will be trapped within the iron crystals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] When rapidly cooled, a diffusionless (martensite) transformation occurs, in which the carbon atoms become trapped in solution.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] This causes the iron crystals to deform as the crystal structure tries to change to its low temperature state, leaving those crystals very hard but much less ductile (more brittle).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] While the high strength of steel results when diffusion and precipitation is prevented (forming martensite), most heat-treatable alloys are precipitation hardening alloys, that depend on the diffusion of alloying elements to achieve their strength.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] When heated to form a solution and then cooled quickly, these alloys become much softer than normal, during the diffusionless transformation, but then harden as they age.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The solutes in these alloys will precipitate over time, forming intermetallic phases, which are difficult to discern from the base metal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Unlike steel, in which the solid solution separates into different crystal phases (carbide and ferrite), precipitation hardening alloys form different phases within the same crystal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] These intermetallic alloys appear homogeneous in crystal structure, but tend to behave heterogeneously, becoming hard and somewhat brittle.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In 1906, precipitation hardening alloys were discovered by Alfred Wilm.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Precipitation hardening alloys, such as certain alloys of aluminium, titanium, and copper, are heat-treatable alloys that soften when quenched (cooled quickly), and then harden over time.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Wilm had been searching for a way to harden aluminium alloys for use in machine-gun cartridge cases.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Knowing that aluminium-copper alloys were heat-treatable to some degree, Wilm tried quenching a ternary alloy of aluminium, copper, and the addition of magnesium, but was initially disappointed with the results.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, when Wilm retested it the next day he discovered that the alloy increased in hardness when left to age at room temperature, and far exceeded his expectations.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Although an explanation for the phenomenon was not provided until 1919, duralumin was one of the first "age hardening" alloys used, becoming the primary building material for the first Zeppelins, and was soon followed by many others.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Because they often exhibit a combination of high strength and low weight, these alloys became widely used in many forms of industry, including the construction of modern aircraft.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] When a molten metal is mixed with another substance, there are two mechanisms that can cause an alloy to form, called *atom exchange* and the *interstitial mechanism*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The relative size of each element in the mix plays a primary role in determining which mechanism will occur.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] When the atoms are relatively similar in size, the atom exchange method usually happens, where some of the atoms composing the metallic crystals are substituted with atoms of the other constituent.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] This is called a *substitutional alloy*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Examples of substitutional alloys include bronze and brass, in which some of the copper atoms are substituted with either tin or zinc atoms respectively.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In the case of the interstitial mechanism, one atom is usually much smaller than the other and can not successfully substitute for the other type of atom in the crystals of the base metal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Instead, the smaller atoms become trapped in the interstitial sites between the atoms of the crystal matrix.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] This is referred to as an *interstitial alloy*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Steel is an example of an interstitial alloy, because the very small carbon atoms fit into interstices of the iron matrix.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Stainless steel is an example of a combination of interstitial and substitutional alloys, because the carbon atoms fit into the interstices, but some of the iron atoms are substituted by nickel and chromium atoms.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The use of alloys by humans started with the use of meteoric iron, a naturally occurring alloy of nickel and iron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] It is the main constituent of iron meteorites.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] As no metallurgic processes were used to separate iron from nickel, the alloy was used as it was.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Meteoric iron could be forged from a red heat to make objects such as tools, weapons, and nails.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In many cultures it was shaped by cold hammering into knives and arrowheads.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Meteoric iron was very rare and valuable, and difficult for ancient people to work.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Iron is usually found as iron ore on Earth, except for one deposit of native iron in Greenland, which was used by the Inuit.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Native copper, however, was found worldwide, along with silver, gold, and platinum, which were also used to make tools, jewelry, and other objects since Neolithic times.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Copper was the hardest of these metals, and the most widely distributed.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] It became one of the most important metals to the ancients.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Starting around 10,000 years ago in the highlands of Anatolia (Turkey), humans learned to smelt metals such as copper and tin from ore.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Early bronze alloys used copper and arsenic, but the latter can be toxic to the metal-workers.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Around 2500 BC, people began alloying tin and copper to form bronze, which was much harder than its ingredients.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, tin was rare, being found mostly in Great Britain.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In the Middle East, people began alloying copper with zinc to form brass.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Ancient civilizations took into account the mixture and the various properties it produced, such as hardness, toughness and melting point, under various conditions of temperature and work hardening, developing much of the information contained in modern alloy phase diagrams.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] For example, arrowheads from the Chinese Qin dynasty (around 200 BC) were often constructed with a hard bronze-head, but a softer bronze-tang, combining the alloys to prevent both dulling and breaking during use.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Mercury has been smelted from cinnabar for thousands of years.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Mercury dissolves many metals, such as gold, silver, and tin, to form amalgams (an alloy in a soft paste or liquid form at ambient temperature).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Amalgams have been used since 200 BC in China for gilding objects such as armor and mirrors with precious metals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The ancient Romans often used mercury-tin amalgams for gilding their armor.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The amalgam was applied as a paste and then heated until the mercury vaporized, leaving the gold, silver, or tin behind.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Mercury was often used in mining, to extract precious metals like gold and silver from their ores.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Many ancient civilizations alloyed metals for purely aesthetic purposes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In ancient Egypt and Mycenae, gold was often alloyed with copper to produce red-gold, or iron to produce a bright burgundy-gold.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Gold was often found alloyed with silver or other metals to produce various types of colored gold.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] These metals were also used to strengthen each other, for more practical purposes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Copper was often added to silver to make sterling silver, increasing its strength for use in dishes, silverware, and other practical items.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Quite often, precious metals were alloyed with less valuable substances as a means to deceive buyers.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Around 250 BC, Archimedes was commissioned by the King of Syracuse to find a way to check the purity of the gold in a crown, leading to the famous bath-house shouting of "Eureka!" upon the discovery of Archimedes' principle.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The term pewter covers a variety of alloys consisting primarily of tin.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] As a pure metal, tin is much too soft to use for most practical purposes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, during the Bronze Age, tin was a rare metal in many parts of Europe and the Mediterranean, so it was often valued higher than gold.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] To make jewellery, cutlery, or other objects from tin, workers usually alloyed it with other metals to increase strength and hardness.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] These metals were typically lead, antimony, bismuth or copper.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] These solutes were sometimes added individually in varying amounts, or added together, making a wide variety of objects, ranging from practical items such as dishes, surgical tools, candlesticks or funnels, to decorative items like ear rings and hair clips.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The earliest examples of pewter come from ancient Egypt, around 1450 BC.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The use of pewter was widespread across Europe, from France to Norway and Britain (where most of the ancient tin was mined) to the Near East.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The alloy was also used in China and the Far East, arriving in Japan around 800 AD, where it was used for making objects like ceremonial vessels, tea canisters, or chalices used in shinto shrines.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The first known smelting of iron began in Anatolia, around 1800 BC.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Called the bloomery process, it produced very soft but ductile wrought iron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] By 800 BC, iron-making technology had spread to Europe, arriving in Japan around 700 AD.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Pig iron, a very hard but brittle alloy of iron and carbon, was being produced in China as early as 1200 BC, but did not arrive in Europe until the Middle Ages.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Pig iron has a lower melting point than iron, and was used for making cast iron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, these metals found little practical use until the introduction of crucible steel around 300 BC.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] These steels were of poor quality, and the introduction of pattern welding, around the 1st century AD, sought to balance the extreme properties of the alloys by laminating them, to create a tougher metal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Around 700 AD, the Japanese began folding bloomery-steel and cast iron in alternating layers to increase the strength of their swords, using clay fluxes to remove slag and impurities.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] This method of Japanese swordsmithing produced one of the purest steel-alloys of the ancient world.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] While the use of iron started to become more widespread around 1200 BC, mainly because of interruptions in the trade routes for tin, the metal was much softer than bronze.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, very small amounts of steel, (an alloy of iron and around 1% carbon), was always a byproduct of the bloomery process.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The ability to modify the hardness of steel by heat treatment had been known since 1100 BC, and the rare material was valued for the manufacture of tools and weapons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Because the ancients could not produce temperatures high enough to melt iron fully, the production of steel in decent quantities did not occur until the introduction of blister steel during the Middle Ages.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] This method introduced carbon by heating wrought iron in charcoal for long periods of time, but the absorption of carbon in this manner is extremely slow thus the penetration was not very deep, so the alloy was not homogeneous.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In 1740, Benjamin Huntsman began melting blister steel in a crucible to even out the carbon content, creating the first process for the mass production of tool steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Huntsman's process was used for manufacturing tool steel until the early 1900s.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The introduction of the blast furnace to Europe in the Middle Ages meant that people could produce pig iron in much higher volumes than wrought iron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Because pig iron could be melted, people began to develop processes to reduce carbon in liquid pig iron to create steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Puddling had been used in China since the first century, and was introduced in Europe during the 1700s, where molten pig iron was stirred while exposed to the air, to remove the carbon by oxidation.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In 1858, Henry Bessemer developed a process of steel-making by blowing hot air through liquid pig iron to reduce the carbon content.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The Bessemer process led to the first large scale manufacture of steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Steel is an alloy of iron and carbon, but the term *alloy steel* usually only refers to steels that contain other elements— like vanadium, molybdenum, or cobalt—in amounts sufficient to alter the properties of the base steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Since ancient times, when steel was used primarily for tools and weapons, the methods of producing and working the metal were often closely guarded secrets.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Even long after the Age of Enlightenment, the steel industry was very competitive and manufacturers went through great lengths to keep their processes confidential, resisting any attempts to scientifically analyze the material for fear it would reveal their methods.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] For example, the people of Sheffield, a center of steel production in England, were known to routinely bar visitors and tourists from entering town to deter industrial espionage.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Thus, almost no metallurgical information existed about steel until 1860.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Afterward, many people began experimenting with various alloys of steel without much success.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, in 1882, Robert Hadfield, being a pioneer in steel metallurgy, took an interest and produced a steel alloy containing around 12% manganese.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Called mangalloy, it exhibited extreme hardness and toughness, becoming the first commercially viable alloy-steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Afterward, he created silicon steel, launching the search for other possible alloys of steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Robert Forester Mushet found that by adding tungsten to steel it could produce a very hard edge that would resist losing its hardness at high temperatures.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Mushet's special steel" (RMS) became the first high-speed steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Mushet's steel was quickly replaced by tungsten carbide steel, developed by Taylor and White in 1900, in which they doubled the tungsten content and added small amounts of chromium and vanadium, producing a superior steel for use in lathes and machining tools.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In 1903, the Wright brothers used a chromium-nickel steel to make the crankshaft for their airplane engine, while in 1908 Henry Ford began using vanadium steels for parts like crankshafts and valves in his Model T Ford, due to their higher strength and resistance to high temperatures.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In 1912, the Krupp Ironworks in Germany developed a rust-resistant steel by adding 21% chromium and 7% nickel, producing the first stainless steel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] A typical example of a modern alloy is 304 grade stainless steel which is commonly used for kitchen utensils, pans, knives and forks.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Sometime also known as 18/8, it as an alloy consisting broadly of 74% iron, 18% chromium and 8% nickel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The chromium and nickel alloying elements add strength and hardness to the majority iron element, but their main function is to make it resistant to rust/corrosion.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Due to their high reactivity, most metals were not discovered until the 19th century.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] A method for extracting aluminium from bauxite was proposed by Humphry Davy in 1807, using an electric arc.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Although his attempts were unsuccessful, by 1855 the first sales of pure aluminium reached the market.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, as extractive metallurgy was still in its infancy, most aluminium extraction-processes produced unintended alloys contaminated with other elements found in the ore; the most abundant of which was copper.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] These aluminium-copper alloys (at the time termed "aluminium bronze") preceded pure aluminium, offering greater strength and hardness over the soft, pure metal, and to a slight degree were found to be heat treatable.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] However, due to their softness and limited hardenability these alloys found little practical use, and were more of a novelty, until the Wright brothers used an aluminium alloy to construct the first airplane engine in 1903.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] During the time between 1865 and 1910, processes for extracting many other metals were discovered, such as chromium, vanadium, tungsten, iridium, cobalt, and molybdenum, and various alloys were developed.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] Prior to 1910, research mainly consisted of private individuals tinkering in their own laboratories.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] The Doehler Die Casting Co. of Toledo, Ohio were known for the production of *Brastil*, a high tensile corrosion resistant bronze alloy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] As a part of industrial procurement for the production of precision alloys, intermediate good 'master alloy' ingots or powder are produced with a consistent mixture of desired metal content.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] These master alloys can then be combined to produce the final desired alloy for production.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/alloy] In the aluminium alloy industry, master alloy is commonly introduced to aluminium to adjust the metal grain of the final alloy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The **atomic radius** of a chemical element is a measure of the size of its atom, usually the mean or typical distance from the center of the nucleus to the outermost isolated electron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Since the boundary is not a well-defined physical entity, there are various non-equivalent definitions of atomic radius.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Five widely used definitions of atomic radius are covalent radius, Van der Waals radius, charge radius, ionic radius, and metallic radius.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Typically, because of the difficulty to isolate atoms in order to measure their radii separately, the atomic radius is measured in a chemically bonded state; however, theoretical calculations are simpler when considering atoms in isolation.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The dependencies on environment, probe, and state lead to a multiplicity of definitions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Depending on the definition, the term may apply to atoms in condensed matter, covalently bonding in molecules, or in ionized and excited states; and its value may be obtained through experimental measurements, or computed from theoretical models.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The value of the radius may depend on the atom's state and context.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Electrons do not have definite orbits nor sharply defined ranges.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Rather, their positions must be described as probability distributions that taper off gradually as one moves away from the nucleus, without a sharp cutoff; these are referred to as atomic orbitals or electron clouds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Moreover, in condensed matter and molecules, the electron clouds of the atoms usually overlap to some extent, and some of the electrons may roam over a large region encompassing two or more atoms.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Under most definitions the radii of isolated neutral atoms range between 30 and 300 pm (trillionths of a meter), or between 0.3 and 3 ångströms.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Therefore, the radius of an atom is more than 10,000 times the radius of its nucleus (1–10 fm), and less than 1/1000 of the wavelength of visible light (400–700 nm).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] For many purposes, atoms can be modeled as spheres.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] This is only a crude approximation, but it can provide quantitative explanations and predictions for many phenomena, such as the density of liquids and solids, the diffusion of fluids through molecular sieves, the arrangement of atoms and ions in crystals, and the size and shape of molecules.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The first to estimate the radius of an atom was Johann Chrysostom Magnenus in 1646.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] He was at Mass and noticed the smell of incense permeating the church.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] He knew the size of the incense and estimated the size of the church.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] He presumed that he could detect the incense if one atom was in each nostril.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] He also presumed that the incense was distributed homogenously throughout the church.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] With these assumptions he was able to estimate the size of an atom to be about 10 to the power of −24 cubic metres.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] (The units he used have been converted to metric to make comparisons with later estimates easier.) Taking the cube root this gives an estimate of the atomic radius to be about 10 to the power of −8 metres.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] This is somewhat larger than current estimates but given the assumptions made in the calculation is very good.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] These calculations were published in his work *Democritus reviviscens sive de atomis*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The concept of atomic radius was preceded in the 19th century by the concept of atomic volume, a relative measure of how much space would on average an atom occupy in a given solid or liquid material.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] By the end of the century this term was also used in an absolute sense, as a molar volume divided by Avogadro constant.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Such a volume is different for different crystalline forms even of the same compound, but physicists used it for rough, order-of-magnitude estimates of the atomic size, getting 10−8–10−7 cm for copper.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The earliest estimates of the atomic size was made by opticians in the 1830s, particularly Cauchy, who developed models of light dispersion assuming a lattice of connected "molecules".
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] In 1857 Clausius developed a gas-kinetic model which included the equation for mean free path.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] In the 1870s it was used to estimate gas molecule sizes, as well as an aforementioned comparison with visible light wavelength and an estimate from the thickness of soap bubble film at which its contractile force rapidly diminishes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] By 1900, various estimates of mercury atom diameter averaged around 275±20 pm (modern estimates give 300±10 pm, see below).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] In 1920, shortly after it had become possible to determine the sizes of atoms using X-ray crystallography, it was suggested that all atoms of the same element have the same radii.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] However, in 1923, when more crystal data had become available, it was found that the approximation of an atom as a sphere does not necessarily hold when comparing the same atom in different crystal structures.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The following table shows empirically measured **covalent** radii for the elements, as published by J.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The values are in picometers (pm or 1×10−12 m), with an accuracy of about 5 pm.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The shade of the box ranges from red to yellow as the radius increases; gray indicates lack of data.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Electrons in atoms fill electron shells from the lowest available energy level.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] As a consequence of the Aufbau principle, each new period begins with the first two elements filling the next unoccupied s-orbital.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Because an atom's s-orbital electrons are typically farthest from the nucleus, this results in a significant increase in atomic radius with the first elements of each period.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The atomic radius of each element generally decreases across each period due to an increasing number of protons, since an increase in the number of protons increases the attractive force acting on the atom's electrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The greater attraction draws the electrons closer to the protons, decreasing the size of the atom.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Down each group, the atomic radius of each element typically increases because there are more occupied electron energy levels and therefore a greater distance between protons and electrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The increasing nuclear charge is partly counterbalanced by the increasing number of electrons—a phenomenon that is known as shielding—which explains why the size of atoms usually increases down each column despite an increase in attractive force from the nucleus.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Electron shielding causes the attraction of an atom's nucleus on its electrons to decrease, so electrons occupying higher energy states farther from the nucleus experience reduced attractive force, increasing the size of the atom.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] However, elements in the 5d-block (lutetium to mercury) are much smaller than this trend predicts due to the weak shielding of the 4f-subshell.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] This phenomenon is known as the lanthanide contraction.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] A similar phenomenon exists for actinides; however, the general instability of transuranic elements makes measurements for the remainder of the 5f-block difficult and for transactinides nearly impossible.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Finally, for sufficiently heavy elements, the atomic radius may be decreased by relativistic effects.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] This is a consequence of electrons near the strongly charged nucleus traveling at a sufficient fraction of the speed of light to gain a nontrivial amount of mass.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The electrons in the 4f-subshell, which is progressively filled from lanthanum (*Z* = 57) to ytterbium (*Z* = 70), are not particularly effective at shielding the increasing nuclear charge from the sub-shells further out.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The elements immediately following the lanthanides have atomic radii which are smaller than would be expected and which are almost identical to the atomic radii of the elements immediately above them.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Hence lutetium is in fact slightly smaller than yttrium, hafnium has virtually the same atomic radius (and chemistry) as zirconium, and tantalum has an atomic radius similar to niobium, and so forth.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The effect of the lanthanide contraction is noticeable up to platinum (*Z* = 78), after which it is masked by a relativistic effect known as the inert-pair effect.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] There is a regular decrease in their ionic radii.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] There is a regular decrease in their tendency to act as a reducing agent, with an increase in atomic number.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The second and third rows of d-block transition elements are quite close in properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] Consequently, these elements occur together in natural minerals and are difficult to separate.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The d-block contraction is less pronounced than the lanthanide contraction but arises from a similar cause.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] In this case, it is the poor shielding capacity of the 3d-electrons which affects the atomic radii and chemistries of the elements immediately following the first row of the transition metals, from gallium (*Z* = 31) to bromine (*Z* = 35).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/atomic-radius] The following table shows atomic radii computed from theoretical models, as published by Enrico Clementi and others in 1967.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] With the CALPHAD method one collects all experimental information on phase equilibria in a system and all thermodynamic information obtained from thermochemical and thermophysical studies.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] The thermodynamic properties of each phase are then described with a mathematical model containing adjustable parameters.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] The parameters are evaluated by optimizing the fit of the model to all the information, also involving coexisting phases.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] It is then possible to recalculate the phase diagram as well as the thermodynamic properties of all the phases.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] There are two crucial factors for the success of the CALPHAD method.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] The first factor is to find realistic as well as convenient mathematical models for the Gibbs energy for each phase.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] The Gibbs energy is used because most experimental data have been determined at known temperature and pressure and any other thermodynamic quantities can be calculated from it.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] It is not possible to obtain an exact description of the behavior of the Gibbs energy of a multi-component system with analytical expressions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] It is thus necessary to identify the main features and base the mathematical models on them.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] The discrepancy between model and reality is finally represented by a power series expansion in temperature, pressure and constitution of the phase.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] The adjustable parameters of these model descriptions are refined to reproduce the experimental data.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] The strength of the CALPHAD method is that the descriptions of the constituent sub-systems can be combined to describe a multi-component system.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] The second crucial factor is the availability of computer software for calculating equilibria and various kinds of diagrams and databases with the stored assessed information.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] As there are at present many different kinds of models used for different kinds of phases there are several thermodynamic databases available, either free or commercially, for different materials like steels, super-alloys, semiconductor materials, aqueous solutions, slags, etc.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] There are also several different kinds of software available using different kinds of algorithms for computing the equilibrium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] CALPHAD had a slow start in the 60s but sophisticated thermodynamic data bank systems started to appear in the 80s and today there are several commercial products on the market, e.g.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] FactSage, MTDATA, PANDAT, MatCalc, JMatPro, and Thermo-Calc as well as open-sources codes such as OpenCalphad, PyCalphad, and ESPEI.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/calphad] There is a journal with this name where recent scientific achievements are published but scientific papers describing the use of the CALPHAD methods are published also in many other journals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] A **chemical element** is a species of atom defined by its number of protons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The number of protons is called the atomic number of that element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, oxygen has an atomic number of 8: each oxygen atom has 8 protons in its nucleus.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Atoms of the same element can have different numbers of neutrons in their nuclei, known as isotopes of the element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Atoms of one element can be transformed into atoms of a different element in nuclear reactions, which change an atom's atomic number.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Almost all baryonic matter in the universe is composed of elements (among rare exceptions are neutron stars).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The term "chemical element" is also widely used to mean a pure chemical substance consisting of a single element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, oxygen gas consists only of atoms of oxygen.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Historically, the term "chemical element" meant a substance that cannot be broken down into constituent substances by chemical reactions, and for most practical purposes this definition still has validity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] There was some controversy in the 1920s over whether isotopes deserved to be recognised as separate elements if they could be separated by chemical means.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] By November 2016, the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) recognized a total of 118 elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The first 94 occur naturally on Earth, and the remaining 24 are synthetic elements produced in nuclear reactions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Save for unstable radioactive elements (radioelements) which decay quickly, nearly all elements are available industrially in varying amounts.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The discovery and synthesis of further new elements is an ongoing area of scientific study.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The history of the discovery and use of elements began with early human societies that discovered native minerals such as carbon, sulfur, copper, and gold (though the modern concept of an element was not yet understood).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Attempts to classify materials such as these resulted in the concepts of classical elements, alchemy, and similar theories throughout history.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Much of the modern understanding of elements developed from the work of Dmitri Mendeleev, a Russian chemist who published the first recognizable periodic table in 1869.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This table organizes the elements by increasing atomic number into rows ("periods") in which the columns ("groups") share recurring ("periodic") physical and chemical properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The periodic table summarizes various properties of the elements, allowing chemists to derive relationships between them and to make predictions about exceedingly transient nuclides not yet observed, and the potential compounds these unknown elements might form.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The term "(chemical) element" is used in two different but closely related meanings: it can mean a chemical substance consisting of a single kind of atom (a free element), or it can mean that kind of atom as a component of various chemical substances.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, water (H2O) consists of the elements hydrogen (H) and oxygen (O) even though it does not contain the chemical substances (di)hydrogen (H2) and (di)oxygen (O2), as H2O molecules are different from H2 and O2 molecules.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For the meaning "chemical substance consisting of a single kind of atom", the terms "elementary substance" and "simple substance" have been suggested, but they have not gained much acceptance in English chemical literature, whereas in some other languages their equivalent is widely used.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, French distinguishes *élément chimique* (kind of atoms) and *corps simple* (chemical substance consisting of one kind of atom); Russian distinguishes химический элемент and простое вещество.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Chemical elements can be organized by name, chemical symbol, and also by properties (as atoms or as substances).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The properties of chemical elements as kinds of atom include the atomic number, atomic weight, isotopes, abundance in nature, ionization energy, electron affinity, oxidation states, and electronegativity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The radioactive nuclides can be arranged by length of half-life.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] As substances, the properties of chemical elements include their density, melting point, boiling point, electrical conductance, thermal conductivity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] One of the most convenient, and certainly the most traditional presentation of the elements, is in the form of the periodic table, which groups together elements with similar chemical properties (and usually also similar electronic structures).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Chemical elements can be categorised by their origin on Earth, with the first 94 considered naturally occurring, while those with atomic numbers beyond 94 have only been produced artificially via human-made nuclear reactions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The lightest elements are hydrogen and helium, both created by Big Bang nucleosynthesis in the first 20 minutes of the universe in a ratio of around 3:1 by mass (or 12:1 by number of atoms), along with tiny traces of the next two elements, lithium and beryllium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Almost all other elements found in nature were made by various natural methods of nucleosynthesis.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] On Earth, small amounts of new atoms are naturally produced in nucleogenic reactions, or in cosmogenic processes, such as cosmic ray spallation.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] New atoms are also naturally produced on Earth as radiogenic daughter isotopes of ongoing radioactive decay processes such as alpha decay, beta decay, spontaneous fission, cluster decay, and other rarer modes of decay.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] "Known" here means observed well enough, even from just a few decay products, to have been differentiated from other elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Most recently, the synthesis of element 118 (since named oganesson) was reported in October 2006, and the synthesis of element 117 (tennessine) was reported in April 2010.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Of these 118 elements, the first 94 elements have been detected directly on Earth as primordial nuclides present from the formation of the Solar System, or as naturally occurring fission or transmutation products of uranium and thorium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Six of these occur in extreme trace amounts: technetium, atomic number 43; promethium, number 61; astatine, number 85; francium, number 87; neptunium, number 93; and plutonium, number 94.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] These 94 elements have been detected in the universe at large, in the spectra of stars, as well as neutron star mergers and supernovae, where short-lived radioactive elements are newly being made.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Two or more atoms can combine to form molecules.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Some elements form molecules of atoms of said element only: e.g. atoms of hydrogen (H) form diatomic molecules (H2).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Chemical compounds are substances made of atoms of different elements; they can have molecular or non-molecular structure.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Mixtures are materials containing different chemical substances; that means (in case of molecular substances) that they contain different types of molecules.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] When different elements undergo chemical reactions, atoms are rearranged into new compounds held together by chemical bonds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Less than twenty elements, including the gold, platinum, iron group metals, can sometimes be found uncombined as relatively pure native element minerals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Nearly all other naturally occurring elements exist in the Earth as compounds or mixtures.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Air is mostly a mixture of molecular nitrogen and oxygen, though it does contain compounds including carbon dioxide and water, as well as atomic argon, a noble gas which is chemically inert and therefore does not undergo chemical reactions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The standard model of an atom is of a dense nucleus of charged protons and electrically-neutral neutrons, surrounded by an electrically-bound cloud of low mass, negatively charged electrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Despite the force of mutual repulsion between the protons, the nucleus is held together by the short-ranged strong nuclear force between the particles.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The neutron–proton ratio determines the stability of a nucleus, as a proper balance of neutrons counteracts the mutual repulsion of the protons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] A nuclide, or nuclear species, is a class of atoms characterized by their number of protons, *Z*, their number of neutrons, *N*, and their nuclear energy state.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Atomic nuclei other than 1 1H, a lone proton, consist of protons and neutrons bound together by the residual strong force, overcoming electrical repulsion between protons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For that reason, neutrons are required to bind protons together; as the number of protons increases, so does the neutron–proton ratio necessary for stability.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, although light elements up through oxygen have stable nuclides with the same number of neutrons as protons, lead requires about 3 neutrons for 2 protons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The atomic number of an element is equal to the number of protons in each atom, and defines the element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, all carbon atoms contain 6 protons in their atomic nucleus; so the atomic number of carbon is 6.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The number of protons in the nucleus determines its electric charge, which in turn determines the number of bound electrons of an atom in its non-ionized state.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The electrons occupy atomic orbitals that determine the atom's chemical properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Isotopes are atoms of the same element (that is, with the same number of protons in their nucleus), but having *different* numbers of neutrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Thus, for example, there are three main isotopes of carbon.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] All carbon atoms have 6 protons, but they can have either 6, 7, or 8 neutrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Since the mass numbers of these are 12, 13 and 14 respectively, said three isotopes are known as carbon-12, carbon-13, and carbon-14 (12C, 13C, and 14C).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Natural carbon is a mixture of 12C (about 98.9%), 13C (about 1.1%) and about 1 atom per trillion of 14C.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The number of neutrons in a nucleus usually has very little effect on an element's chemical properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] An exception is hydrogen, for which the kinetic isotope effect is significant.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Thus, all carbon isotopes have nearly identical chemical properties because they all have six electrons, even though they may have 6 to 8 neutrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] That is why atomic number, rather than mass number or atomic weight, is considered the identifying characteristic of an element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] All elements have radioactive isotopes (radioisotopes), but many of these radioisotopes are not found in nature due to a low half life.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Radioisotopes typically decay into other elements via alpha decay, beta decay, or inverse beta decay; some isotopes of the heaviest elements also undergo spontaneous fission.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Isotopes that are not radioactive, are termed "stable" isotopes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Isotopes with even numbers of protons, even numbers of neutrons, or both, tend to be more stable as like particle can pair up with like.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This pairing effect allows the identical particles to align with opposite spins, increasing the binding energy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Most (54 of 94) naturally occurring elements have more than one stable isotope.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Only 26 elements are monoisotopic, having exactly one stable isotope; these have an odd atomic number of protons, with the exception of beryllium-9 which has an odd number of neutrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The mean number of stable isotopes for the 80 stable elements is 3.1 stable isotopes per element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The largest number of stable isotopes for a single element is 10 (for tin, element 50).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Elements with atomic numbers 1 through 82 each have at least one stable isotope (except for technetium, element 43 and promethium, element 61, which have no stable isotopes).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However, observationally stable isotopes of some elements (such as tungsten and lead) are predicted to be slightly radioactive with very long half-lives: for example, the half-lives predicted for the observationally stable lead isotopes range from 1035 to 10189 years.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Isotopes are observationally stable when they are theoretically unstable but no radioactive decay has yet been observed.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Out of the over 250 nuclides that are called stable, only 90 are considered theoretically stable, meaning they lack a known decay mode.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Elements with atomic numbers 83 through 94 are unstable enough that radioactive decay of all isotopes can be detected.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Some of these elements, notably bismuth (atomic number 83), thorium (atomic number 90), and uranium (atomic number 92), have one or more isotopes with half-lives long enough to survive from before the Solar System formed.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The remaining longest-lived isotopes have half lives too short for them to have been present at the beginning of the Solar System, and are therefore "transient elements".
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Of these 11 transient elements, five (polonium, radon, radium, actinium, and protactinium) are relatively common decay products of thorium and uranium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The remaining six transient elements (technetium, promethium, astatine, francium, neptunium, and plutonium) occur only rarely, as products of rare decay modes or nuclear reaction processes involving uranium or other heavy elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The remaining 24 heaviest elements (those beyond plutonium, element 94) are radioactive, with half-lives so short that they are not found on Earth and must be synthesized.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Five have been discovered in the spectrum of Przybylski's star, from element 95 (americium) to 99 (einsteinium).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] These are thought to be neutron capture products of uranium and thorium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] All 24 heavier elements are radioactive, with short half-lives; if any of these elements were present when the Earth formed, they are certain to have completely decayed, and if present in novae, are in quantities too small to have been noted.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Technetium was the first purportedly non-naturally occurring element synthesized, in 1937, though traces of technetium have since been found in nature (and also the element may have been discovered naturally in 1925).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This pattern of artificial production and later natural discovery has been repeated with several other radioactive naturally occurring rare elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The lightest radioactive isotope is tritium, which undergoes Beta decay with a half-life of 12.3 years.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] At 2×1019 years, over 109 times the estimated age of the universe, bismuth-209 has the longest known alpha decay half-life of any nuclide, and is almost always considered on par with the 80 stable elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The isotope tellurium-128 transmutes through double beta decay with a half life of 2.25×1024 years, over 100,000 times longer than bismuth-209.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The primary source of radiation exposure from isotope decays in the human body come from carbon-14 and potassium-40 intake, which produce an annual effective dose of 0.17 mSv.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The mass number of an element, *A*, is the number of nucleons (protons and neutrons) in the atomic nucleus.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Different isotopes of a given element are distinguished by their mass number, which is written as a superscript on the left hand side of the chemical symbol (e.g., 238U).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The mass number is always an integer and has units of "nucleons".
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Thus, magnesium-24 (24 is the mass number) is an atom with 24 nucleons (12 protons and 12 neutrons).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Its relative atomic mass is a dimensionless number equal to the atomic mass divided by the atomic mass constant, which equals 1 Da.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In general, the mass number of a given nuclide differs in value slightly from its relative atomic mass.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This mass deficit is primarily due to the nuclear binding energy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, the atomic mass of chlorine-35 to five significant digits is 34.969 Da and that of chlorine-37 is 36.966 Da.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However, the relative atomic mass of each isotope is quite close to its mass number (always within 1%).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The only isotope whose atomic mass is exactly a natural number is 12C, which has a mass of 12 Da; because the dalton is defined as 1/12 of the mass of a free neutral carbon-12 atom in the ground state.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] During the nuclear fusion of lower mass atoms such as hydrogen, the net change in mass deficit is released as energy, as determined by the mass–energy equivalence relationship.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This process of fusing hydrogen atoms into helium is what drives the energy output of the Sun.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Over time, the result is an increasing concentration of helium at the stellar core.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] During the evolution of stars much more massive than the Sun, increasingly massive nuclei are then formed through a type of fusion called the alpha process, until iron-52 is reached.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The binding energy of a nucleus reaches its peak value for isotopes of iron and nickel.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Hence, beyond that point, further fusion results in a lower binding energy, so energy is absorbed rather than released.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] As a result, an inert iron core forms that does not contribute to the star's energy output.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In the nuclear fission process, the resulting particles have a higher net binding energy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This change in the net mass deficit again results in a release of energy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Hence, highly radioactive elements such as uranium-235 can be useful sources of energy production.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The standard atomic weight (commonly called "atomic weight") of an element is the *average* of the atomic masses of all the chemical element's isotopes as found in a particular environment, weighted by isotopic abundance, relative to the atomic mass unit.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This number may be a fraction that is *not* close to a whole number.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, the relative atomic mass of chlorine is 35.453 u, which differs greatly from a whole number as it is an average of about 76% chlorine-35 and 24% chlorine-37.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Whenever a relative atomic mass value differs by more than ≈1% from a whole number, it is due to this averaging effect, as significant amounts of more than one isotope are naturally present in a sample of that element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Chemists and nuclear scientists have different definitions of a *pure element*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In chemistry, a pure element means a substance whose atoms all (or in practice almost all) have the same atomic number, or number of protons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Nuclear scientists, however, define a pure element as one that consists of only one isotope.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, a copper wire is 99.99% chemically pure if 99.99% of its atoms are copper, with 29 protons each.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However it is not isotopically pure since natural copper consists of two stable isotopes, 69% 63Cu and 31% 65Cu, with different numbers of neutrons .
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However, pure gold would be both chemically and isotopically pure, since ordinary gold consists only of one isotope, 197Au.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Quantum mechanics causes the bound electrons to be organized into a set of layered shells.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Each shell can only contain a fixed number of electrons occupying paired orbitals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The electron configurations of these shells mediate the interaction with neighboring atoms and determine the chemical properties of atoms.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The shell configuration determines the structure of the periodic table.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Electrons that are confined to an atom are only allowed to assume certain discrete energy levels.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This restriction, known as quantization, is a fundamental facet of the quantum mechanics theory that predicts the wave-like behavior of particles and energy at the smallest scale.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For atoms, these energy levels are represented by electron subshells, where the wave form of an electron is held in a type of standing wave with a specific wavelength.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Each whole number of wavelengths yields one or more atomic orbitals, which describe each the electron's charge distribution at that energy level.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Every orbital can hold a pair of electrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The arrangement of electrons in an atom's orbitals is called the electron configuration.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] These orbitals and their sub-shells are grouped together in shells, with each shell having a principal quantum number that indicates the energy level.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Each shell can only have a fixed number of electrons, which is given by the formula $2n^{2}$ , where n is 1, 2, 3, 4, and so on.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Hence, the count of electrons each shell can contain are 2, 8, 18, 32, and so forth.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] A shell is represented by a row on the periodic table.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The simplest atom is ordinary hydrogen, which consists of one proton and one electron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In its minimum energy ground state, the electron occupies the first shell, designated *K*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This shell has one subshell designated 1s.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The second element, helium, has two protons, two electrons, and usually two neutrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The second electron occupies the same orbital as the first, completing the shell with spin-paired electrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For lithium there are three electrons, so one needs to occupy an orbital in the second shell, designated *L*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Per the Aufbau principle, the third electron occupies the next lowest available energy subshell, which is 2s.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This process continues, with successive electrons being placed in the next available lowest energy orbital.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Several terms are commonly used to characterise the general physical and chemical properties of the chemical elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] A first distinction is between metals, which readily conduct electricity, nonmetals, which do not, and a small group, the *metalloids*, having intermediate properties and often behaving as semiconductors.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Besides being different by physical properties as substances, metallic and nonmetallic elements have different chemical properties as kinds of atoms: metallic elements form simple cations, whereas nonmetallic elements (and weak metals) form simple anions and oxoanions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] An exception is noble gases, which do not form *simple* anions, whereas oxoanions are known for xenon.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However, some metallic elements in higher oxidation states form oxoanions as well.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Atoms of nonmetallic elements also form compounds with covalent bonds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Distinguishing terms are used for certain sets of the more broadly viewed metals and nonmetals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] These sets include: actinides, alkali metals, alkaline earth metals, halogens, lanthanides, transition metals, post-transition metals, metalloids, reactive nonmetals, and noble gases.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In this system, the alkali metals, alkaline earth metals, and transition metals, as well as the lanthanides and the actinides, are special groups of the metals viewed in a broader sense.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Similarly, the reactive nonmetals and the noble gases are nonmetals viewed in the broader sense.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In some presentations, the halogens are not distinguished, with astatine identified as a metalloid and the others identified as nonmetals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] A more refined classification is often shown in coloured presentations of the periodic table.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The properties of the elements can be summarized in this form, which powerfully and elegantly organizes the elements by physical and chemical properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Each row forms a period of elements that have the same number of electron shells.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] There are 18 numbered groups, each forming its own column of elements whose chemical properties are dominated by the orbital location of the outermost electron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] A block is set of elements sharing atomic orbitals that their valence electrons or vacancies occupy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Use of the periodic table is now ubiquitous in chemistry, providing an extremely useful framework to classify, systematize and compare all the many different forms of chemical behavior.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The table has also found wide application in physics, geology, biology, materials science, engineering, agriculture, medicine, nutrition, environmental health, and astronomy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Its principles are especially important in chemical engineering.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] A commonly used basic distinction among the elements is their state of matter (phase), whether solid, liquid, or gas, at standard temperature and pressure (STP).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Most elements are solids at STP, while several are gases.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Only bromine and mercury are liquid at 0 degrees Celsius (32 degrees Fahrenheit) and 1 atmosphere pressure; caesium and gallium are solid at that temperature, but melt at 28.4 °C (83.1 °F) and 29.8 °C (85.6 °F), respectively.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Melting and boiling points, typically expressed in degrees Celsius at a pressure of one atmosphere, are commonly used in characterizing the various elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Those elements with boiling points above 2,000 C are termed refractory, while those easily vaporized are volatiles.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The element with the widest range between melting and boiling points is gallium, which boils at 2,204 °C (3,999 °F).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] While known for most elements, either or both of these measurements is still undetermined for some of the radioactive elements available in only tiny quantities.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Since helium remains a liquid even at absolute zero at atmospheric pressure, it has only a boiling point, and not a melting point, in conventional presentations.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Atoms of the same element may bond to each other chemically in more than one way, allowing the pure element to exist in multiple chemical structures (spatial arrangements of atoms) which differ in their properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The ability of an element to polymorph in one of many structural forms is known as 'allotropy'.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Non-metallic elements known for polymorphism include carbon, sulfur, phosphorus, oxygen, and nitrogen.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The reference state of an element is defined by convention, usually as the thermodynamically most stable allotrope and physical state at a pressure of 1 bar and a given temperature (typically 298.15 K).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However, for phosphorus, the reference state is white phosphorus even though it is not the most stable allotrope, and the reference state for carbon is graphite, because the structure of graphite is more stable than that of the other allotropes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In thermochemistry, an element is defined to have an enthalpy of formation of zero in its reference state.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Under conditions of stable equilibrium, solid elements are structured into a crystalline form, with each element having its own structure.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] These belong to the seven families of crystal structures: cubic (including body-centered and face-centered), triclinic, hexagonal, monoclinic, orthorhombic, rhombohedral, and tetragonal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Over 30 elements crystallize in the cubic form.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] 40% of the elements form close-packed crystals: either face-centered cubic or hexagonal close-packed.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For some of the synthetically produced transuranic elements, available samples have been too small to determine crystal structures.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Under the high pressure conditions found within a planetary interior, elements can appear in new crystalline forms, forming allotropes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, seven dense classes of silicon crystals can appear at pressures from 1 MPa to 100 GPa, under room temperature conditions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In the extreme conditions found inside a carbon-rich white dwarf, diamond-like amorphous glass may form.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The density at selected standard temperature and pressure (STP) is often used in characterizing the elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The mass density of an element depends on the mass of the atomic nucleus and the separation between the atoms created by the bound electrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Density is given in kilograms per cubic meter (kg/m3), but may also be expressed in grams per cubic centimetre (g/cm3).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Since several elements are gases at commonly encountered temperatures, their densities are usually stated for their gaseous forms; when liquefied or solidified, the gaseous elements have densities similar to those of the other elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The general trend is for densities to increase as the atomic number rises.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Lower density elements are the noble gases and the alkali metals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Higher densities are found in the middle of the rows of the periodic elements, as they can form more covalent bonds, drawing the atoms closer together.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Atoms do not have a fixed radius, but rather their dimension is determined by the charge distribution of their electron cloud.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The measured size depends on the interaction of this cloud with the instrument used to measure it.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Hence, various methods will give similar, but slightly different results.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Along each row of the periodic table, the radius tends to decrease from the alkali metal column to the noble gases.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This is caused by the increasing attraction of the nuclear charge overcoming the mutual repulsion of the electrons as a shell is filled.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] A smaller radius means the atom is less chemically reactive, as the valence electrons are drawn closer to the nucleus.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Depending on the type of chemical bond, the atomic radius determines the atomic separation in a crystal, and hence the mass density.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] When an element has allotropes with different densities, one representative allotrope is typically selected in summary presentations, while densities for each allotrope can be stated where more detail is provided.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, the three familiar allotropes of carbon (amorphous carbon, graphite, and diamond) have densities of 1.8–2.1, 2.267, and 3.515 g/cm3, respectively.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The various chemical elements are formally identified by their unique atomic numbers, their accepted names, and their chemical symbols.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The known elements have atomic numbers from 1 to 118, conventionally presented as Arabic numerals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The terms "light" and "heavy" are sometimes also used informally to indicate relative atomic numbers (not densities), as in "lighter than carbon" or "heavier than lead", though their atomic weights of the elements do not always increase monotonically with their atomic numbers.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, argon with an atomic number of 18 has an atomic weight of 39.95, while potassium with an atomic number of 19 has an atomic weight of 39.098.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] As they were identified as elements, the existing names for anciently known elements (e.g., gold, mercury, iron) were kept in most countries.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] National differences emerged over the element names either for convenience, linguistic niceties, or nationalism.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In the past, the name for new elements was traditionally decided by their discoverers.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This changed in 1947, when a conference of the International Union of Pure and Applied Chemistry (IUPAC) decided that the names and symbols of new elements would be determined by the IUPAC.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The discoverer of a new element had the right to suggest a name, but for purposes of international communication and trade, the official names of the chemical elements both ancient and more recently recognised are decided by the IUPAC.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The IUPAC organization has decided on a style of international English language as a *Lingua franca*, drawing on traditional English names even when an element's chemical symbol is based on a Latin or other traditional word.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, adopting "gold" rather than "aurum" as the name for the 79th element (Au).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] IUPAC prefers the British spellings "aluminium" and "caesium" over the U.S. spellings "aluminum" and "cesium", and the U.S.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However, elements that are practical to sell in bulk in many countries often still have locally used national names, and countries whose national language does not use the Latin alphabet are likely to use the IUPAC element names.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] New elements have been named for their properties, after a mineral from which it was extracted, the location of its discovery, a mythical subject, an astronomical object, or a prominent scientist.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] According to IUPAC, element names are not proper nouns; therefore, the full name of an element is not capitalised in English, even if derived from a proper noun, as in californium and einsteinium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Isotope names are also uncapitalised if written out, *e.g.,* carbon-12 or uranium-235.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Chemical element *symbols* (such as Cf for californium and Es for einsteinium), are always capitalised.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In the second half of the 20th century, physics laboratories became able to produce elements with half-lives too short for an appreciable amount of them to exist at any time.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] These are also named by IUPAC, which generally adopts the name chosen by the discoverer.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This practice can lead to the controversial question of which research group actually discovered an element, a question that delayed the naming of elements with atomic number of 104 and higher for a considerable amount of time.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Precursors of such controversies involved the nationalistic namings of elements in the late 19th century.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, *lutetium* was named after Paris, France.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The Germans were reluctant to relinquish naming rights to the French, often calling it *cassiopeium*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Similarly, the British discoverer of *niobium* originally named it *columbium*, in reference to the New World.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] It was used extensively as such by American publications before the international standardisation (in 1950).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Before chemistry became a science, alchemists designed arcane symbols for both metals and common compounds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] These were however used as abbreviations in diagrams or procedures; there was no concept of atoms combining to form molecules.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] With his advances in the atomic theory of matter, John Dalton devised his own simpler symbols, based on circles, to depict atoms and molecules.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The current system of chemical notation was invented by Jöns Jacob Berzelius in 1814.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In this system, chemical symbols are not mere abbreviations—though each consists of letters of the Latin alphabet.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] They are intended as universal symbols for people of all languages and alphabets.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Since Latin was the common language of science at Berzelius' time, his symbols were abbreviations based on the Latin names of elements (they may be Classical Latin names of elements known since antiquity or Neo-Latin coinages for later elements).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The symbols are not followed by a period (full stop) as with abbreviations.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In most cases, Latin names of elements as used by Berzelius have the same roots as the modern English name.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, hydrogen has the symbol "H" from Neo-Latin *hydrogenium*, which has the same Greek roots as English *hydrogen*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However, in eleven cases Latin (as used by Berzelius) and English names of elements have different roots.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The three other mismatches between Neo-Latin (as used by Berzelius) and English names are "Na" (Neo-Latin *natrium*) for sodium, "K" (Neo-Latin *kalium*) for potassium, and "W" (Neo-Latin *wolframium*) for tungsten.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] These mismatches came from different suggestings of naming the elements in the Modern era.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Initially Berzelius had suggested "So" and "Po" for sodium and potassium, but he changed the symbols to "Na" and "K" later in the same year.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Elements discovered after 1814 were also assigned unique chemical symbols, based on the name of the element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The use of Latin as the universal language of science was fading, but chemical names of newly discovered elements came to be borrowed from language to language with little or no modification.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Other languages sometimes modify element name spellings: Spanish *iterbio* (ytterbium), Italian *afnio* (hafnium), Swedish *moskovium* (moscovium); but those modifications do not affect chemical symbols: Yb, Hf, Mc.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Chemical symbols are understood internationally when element names might require translation.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] There have been some differences in the past.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, Germans in the past have used "J" (for the name *Jod*) for iodine, but now use "I" and *Iod*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The first letter of a chemical symbol is always capitalised, and the subsequent letters, if any, are always lowercase; see the preceding examples.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] There are also symbols in chemical equations for groups of elements, for example in comparative formulas.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] These are often a single capital letter, and the letters are reserved and not used for names of specific elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, "**X**" indicates a variable group (usually a halogen) in a class of compounds, while "**R**" is a radical, meaning a compound structure such as a hydrocarbon chain.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The letter "**Q**" is reserved for "heat" in a chemical reaction.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] "**Y**" is also often used as a general chemical symbol, though it is also the symbol of yttrium and tyrosine.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] "**Z**" is also often used as a general variable group.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] "**E**" is used in organic chemistry to denote an electron-withdrawing group or an electrophile; similarly "**Nu**" denotes a nucleophile.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] "**L**" is used to represent a general ligand in inorganic and organometallic chemistry.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] "**M**" is often used in place of a general metal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] At least two other, two-letter generic chemical symbols are also in informal use, "**Ln**" for any lanthanide and "**An**" for any actinide.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] "**Rg**" was formerly used for any rare gas element, but the group of rare gases has now been renamed noble gases and "**Rg**" now refers to roentgenium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Isotopes of an element are distinguished by mass number (total protons and neutrons), with this number combined with the element's symbol.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] IUPAC prefers that isotope symbols be written in superscript notation when practical, for example 12C and 235U.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However, other notations, such as carbon-12 and uranium-235, or C-12 and U-235, are also used.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] As a special case, the three naturally occurring isotopes of hydrogen are often specified as **H** for 1H (protium), **D** for 2H (deuterium), and **T** for 3H (tritium).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This convention is easier to use in chemical equations, replacing the need to write out the mass number each time.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Thus, the formula for heavy water may be written D2O instead of 2H2O.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Only about 4.6% of the total mass of the universe is made of ordinary matter, including atoms or ions represented by elements, plus neutrinos and photons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The rest of the mass (63%) is an unknown dark matter that is not composed of atoms of elements because it contains no protons, neutrons, or electrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The remaining non-matter part of the mass of the universe is composed of the even less well understood dark energy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The 94 naturally occurring elements were produced by at least four classes of astrophysical process.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Most of the hydrogen, helium and a very small quantity of lithium were produced in the first few minutes of the Big Bang.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] This Big Bang nucleosynthesis happened only once; the other processes are ongoing.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Nuclear fusion inside stars produces elements through stellar nucleosynthesis, including all elements from carbon to iron in atomic number.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Elements higher in atomic number than iron, including heavy elements like uranium and plutonium, are produced by various forms of explosive nucleosynthesis in supernovae and neutron star mergers.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The light elements lithium, beryllium and boron are produced mostly through cosmic ray spallation (fragmentation induced by cosmic rays) of carbon, nitrogen, and oxygen.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In the early phases of the Big Bang, nucleosynthesis of hydrogen resulted in the production of hydrogen-1 (protium, 1H) and helium-4 (4He), as well as a smaller amount of deuterium (2H) and tiny amounts (on the order of 10−10) of lithium and beryllium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Even smaller amounts of boron may have been produced in the Big Bang, since it has been observed in some very old stars, while carbon has not.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] No elements heavier than boron were produced in the Big Bang.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] As a result, the primordial abundance of atoms (or ions) consisted of ~75% 1H, 25% 4He, and 0.01% deuterium, with only tiny traces of lithium, beryllium, and perhaps boron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Subsequent enrichment of galactic halos occurred due to stellar nucleosynthesis and supernova nucleosynthesis.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However, the element abundance in intergalactic space can still closely resemble primordial conditions, unless it has been enriched by a galactic wind or some other means.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] On Earth (and elsewhere), trace amounts of various elements continue to be produced from other elements as products of nuclear transmutation processes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] These include some produced by cosmic rays or other nuclear reactions (see cosmogenic and nucleogenic nuclides), and others produced as decay products of long-lived primordial nuclides.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] For example, trace (but detectable) amounts of carbon-14 (14C) are continually produced in the air by cosmic rays impacting nitrogen atoms, and argon-40 (40Ar) is continually produced by the decay of primordially occurring but unstable potassium-40 (40K).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Three primordially occurring but radioactive actinides, thorium, uranium, and plutonium, decay through a series of recurrently produced but unstable elements such as radium and radon, which are transiently present in any sample of containing these metals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Three other radioactive elements, technetium, promethium, and neptunium, occur only incidentally in natural materials, produced as individual atoms by nuclear fission of the nuclei of various heavy elements or in other rare nuclear processes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Besides the 94 naturally occurring elements, several artificial elements have been produced by nuclear physics technology.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] By 2016, these experiments had produced all elements up to atomic number 118.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] As of 2021, more than a thousand different isotopes have been created through nuclear transmutation, of which 900 do not appear naturally.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The abundance of elements in the Solar System is in keeping with their origin Big Bang nucleosynthesis and a number of progenitor supernova stars.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Very abundant hydrogen and helium are products of the Big Bang, but the next three elements are rare since they had little time to form in the Big Bang and are not made in stars.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] They are, however, produced in small quantities by the breakup of heavier elements in interstellar dust, as a result of impact by cosmic rays.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Beginning with carbon, elements are produced in stars by buildup from alpha particles (helium nuclei), resulting in an alternatingly larger abundance of elements with even atomic numbers, as these are more stable.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] In general, such elements up to the iron peak are made in massive stars in the process of becoming supernovas.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Iron-56 is particularly common, since it is the most stable nuclide that can easily be made from alpha particles, being a product of decay of radioactive nickel-56, ultimately made from 14 helium nuclei.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Elements heavier than iron and up to bismuth are made in neutron capture processes in lower mass stars, and their abundance in the universe (and on Earth) generally decreases with their atomic number.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Nearby galaxies that have evolved along similar lines to the Milky Way have a corresponding enrichment of elements heavier than hydrogen and helium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The more distant galaxies are being viewed as they appeared in the past, so their abundances of elements appear closer to the primordial mixture.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] However, as physical laws and processes appear common throughout the visible universe, scientists expect that these galaxies evolved elements in similar abundance.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The abundance of the chemical elements on Earth varies from air to crust to ocean, and in various types of life.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Oxygen, the most abundant element by mass in the Earth as a whole, is retained on Earth by combination with silicon, magnesium, and iron.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Aluminium at 8% by mass is more common in the Earth's crust compared to the solar abundance, but it is only 2% by mass in the mantle, which has magnesium and iron in place of aluminium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The surface abundance of iron is lower because it has migrated to the Earth's core during the process of planetary differentiation.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] The bulk of all life forms on Earth consist of just six elements, described by the acronym CHNOPS: carbon, hydrogen, nitrogen, oxygen, phosphorus, and sulfur.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p01] Certain kinds of organisms require particular additional elements, for example the magnesium in chlorophyll in green plants, the calcium in mollusc shells, or the iron in the hemoglobin in vertebrates' red blood cells.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The concept of an "element" as an indivisible substance has developed through three major historical phases: Classical definitions (such as those of the ancient Greeks), chemical definitions, and atomic definitions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Ancient philosophy posited a set of classical elements to explain observed patterns in nature.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] These *elements* originally referred to *earth*, *water*, *air* and *fire* rather than the chemical elements of modern science.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The term 'elements' (*stoicheia*) was first used by Greek philosopher Plato around 360 BCE in his dialogue Timaeus, which includes a discussion of the composition of inorganic and organic bodies and is a speculative treatise on chemistry.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Plato believed the elements introduced a century earlier by Empedocles were composed of small polyhedral forms: tetrahedron (fire), octahedron (air), icosahedron (water), and cube (earth).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] 350 BCE, also used the term *stoicheia* and added a fifth element, aether, which formed the heavens.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] In 1661, in *The Sceptical Chymist*, Robert Boyle proposed his theory of corpuscularism, which favoured the analysis of matter as constituted of irreducible units of matter (atoms).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Boyle argued against deciding upon a pre-determined number of elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] This was in contrast with Aristotle's view of the four classical element and Paracelsus' view of three chemical principles of sulfur, mercury, and salt.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Boyle stated his view in four propositions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] In the first and second, he suggests that matter consists of particles, but that these particles may be difficult to separate.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Boyle used the concept of "corpuscles"—or "atomes", as he also called them—to explain how a limited number of elements could combine into a vast number of compounds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Boyle explained that gold reacts with *aqua regia,* and mercury with nitric acid, sulfuric acid, and sulfur to produce various "compounds", and that they could be recovered from those compounds, just as would be expected of elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Yet, Boyle did not consider gold, mercury, or lead elements, but rather—together with wine—"perfectly mixt bodies".
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Even though Boyle is primarily regarded as the first modern chemist, *The Sceptical Chymist* still contains old ideas about the elements, which are alien to a contemporary viewpoint.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] For example, sulfur is not only the familiar yellow non-metal but also an inflammable "spirit".
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] In 1724, in his book *Logick*, the English minister and logician Isaac Watts enumerated the elements then recognised by chemists.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Watts' list of elements included two of Paracelsus' *principles* (sulfur and salt) and two classical elements (earth and water) as well as "spirit".
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Watts did, however, note a lack of consensus among chemists.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The first modern list of elements was given in Antoine Lavoisier's 1789 *Elements of Chemistry*, which contained 33 elements, including light and caloric.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] By 1818, Jöns Jacob Berzelius had determined atomic weights for 45 of the 49 then-accepted elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Russian chemist Dmitri Mendeleev had 63 elements in his 1869 periodic table.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Though earlier precursors to this presentation exist, its invention is generally credited to Mendeleev, who intended the table to illustrate recurring trends in the properties of the elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The layout of the table has been refined and extended over time as new elements have been discovered and new theoretical models have been developed to explain chemical behavior.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] From Boyle until the early 20th century, an element was defined as a pure substance that cannot be decomposed into any simpler substance and cannot be transformed into other elements by chemical processes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Elements at the time were generally distinguished by their atomic weights, a property measurable with fair accuracy by available analytical techniques.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The 1913 discovery by English physicist Henry Moseley that the nuclear charge is the physical basis for the atomic number, further refined when the nature of protons and neutrons became appreciated, eventually led to the current definition of an element based on atomic number (number of protons).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The use of atomic numbers, rather than atomic weights, to distinguish elements has greater predictive value (since these numbers are integers) and also resolves some ambiguities in the chemistry-based view due to varying properties of isotopes and allotropes within the same element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Currently, IUPAC defines an element to exist if it has isotopes with a lifetime longer than the 10−14 seconds it takes the nucleus to form an electronic cloud.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] By 1914, eighty-seven elements were known, all naturally occurring (see Discovery of chemical elements).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The remaining naturally occurring elements were discovered or isolated in subsequent decades, and various additional elements have also been produced synthetically, with much of that work pioneered by Glenn T.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The final naturally-occurring radioactive element, francium, was discovered in 1939 by Marguerite Perey.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] In 1955, element 101 was discovered and named mendelevium in honor of D.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Mendeleev, the first to arrange the elements periodically.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Eleven materials familiar to various prehistoric cultures are now known to be elements: antimony, carbon, copper, gold, iron, lead, mercury, silver, sulfur, tin, and zinc.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Two additional materials now accepted as elements, arsenic and bismuth, were recognised as distinct substances before 1500 AD.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Platinum was known in Pre-Columbian America.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The first recorded discovery of a new element was of phosphorus by the German alchemist Hennig Brand in 1669.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] In 1896 Henri Becquerel serendipitously discovered radioactivity from uranium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The first transuranium element (element with an atomic number greater than 92) discovered was neptunium in 1940.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Since 1999, the IUPAC/IUPAP Joint Working Party has considered claims for the discovery of new elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] As of January 2016, all 118 elements have been confirmed by IUPAC as being discovered.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The discovery of element 112 was acknowledged in 2009, and the name *copernicium* and the chemical symbol *Cn* were suggested for it.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The name and symbol were officially endorsed by IUPAC on 19 February 2010.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] The heaviest element that is believed to have been synthesised to date is element 118, oganesson, on 9 October 2006, by the Flerov Laboratory of Nuclear Reactions in Dubna, Russia.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] Tennessine, element 117 was the latest element claimed to be discovered, in 2009.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/chemical-element-p02] On 28 November 2016, scientists at the IUPAC officially recognised the names for the four newest elements, with atomic numbers 113, 115, 117, and 118.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In crystallography, **crystal structure** is a description of the ordered arrangement of atoms, ions, or molecules in a crystalline material.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Ordered structures occur from the intrinsic nature of constituent particles to form symmetric patterns that repeat along the principal directions of three-dimensional space in matter.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The smallest group of particles in a material that constitutes this repeating pattern is the unit cell of the structure.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The unit cell completely reflects the symmetry and structure of the entire crystal, which is built up by repetitive translation of the unit cell along its principal axes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The translation vectors define the nodes of the Bravais lattice.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The lengths of principal axes/edges, of the unit cell and angles between them are lattice constants, also called *lattice parameters* or *cell parameters*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The symmetry properties of a crystal are described by the concept of space groups.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] All possible symmetric arrangements of particles in three-dimensional space may be described by 230 space groups.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The crystal structure and symmetry play a critical role in determining many physical properties, such as cleavage, electronic band structure, and optical transparency.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Crystal structure is described in terms of the geometry of the arrangement of particles in the unit cells.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The unit cell is defined as the smallest repeating unit having the full symmetry of the crystal structure.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The geometry of the unit cell is defined as a parallelepiped, providing six lattice parameters taken as the lengths of the cell edges (*a*, *b*, *c*) and the angles between them (α, β, γ).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The positions of particles inside the unit cell are described by the fractional coordinates (*xi*, *yi*, *zi*) along the cell edges, measured from a reference point.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] It is thus only necessary to report the coordinates of a smallest asymmetric subset of particles, called the crystallographic asymmetric unit.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The asymmetric unit may be chosen so that it occupies the smallest physical space, which means that not all particles need to be physically located inside the boundaries given by the lattice parameters.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] All other particles of the unit cell are generated by the symmetry operations that characterize the symmetry of the unit cell.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The collection of symmetry operations of the unit cell is expressed formally as the space group of the crystal structure.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Vectors and planes in a crystal lattice are described by the three-value Miller index notation.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] This syntax uses the indices *h*, *k*, and *ℓ* as directional parameters.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] By definition, the syntax (*hkℓ*) denotes a plane that intercepts the three points *a*1/*h*, *a*2/*k*, and *a*3/*ℓ*, or some multiple thereof.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] That is, the Miller indices are proportional to the inverses of the intercepts of the plane with the unit cell (in the basis of the lattice vectors).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] If one or more of the indices is zero, the planes do not intersect that axis (i.e., the intercept is "at infinity").
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] A plane containing a coordinate axis is translated to no longer contain that axis before its Miller indices are determined.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The Miller indices for a plane are integers with no common factors.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Negative indices are indicated with horizontal bars, as in (123).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In an orthogonal coordinate system for a cubic cell, the Miller indices of a plane are the Cartesian components of a vector normal to the plane.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The crystallographic directions are geometric lines linking nodes (atoms, ions or molecules) of a crystal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Likewise, the crystallographic planes are geometric *planes* linking nodes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Some directions and planes have a higher density of nodes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Some directions and planes are defined by symmetry of the crystal system.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In monoclinic, trigonal, tetragonal, and hexagonal systems there is one unique axis (sometimes called the **principal axis**) which has higher rotational symmetry than the other two axes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The **basal plane** is the plane perpendicular to the principal axis in these crystal systems.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] For triclinic, orthorhombic, and cubic crystal systems the axis designation is arbitrary and there is no principal axis.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] For the special case of simple cubic crystals, the lattice vectors are orthogonal and of equal length (usually denoted *a*); similarly for the reciprocal lattice.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] So, in this common case, the Miller indices (*ℓmn*) and [*ℓmn*] both simply denote normals/directions in Cartesian coordinates.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] For face-centered cubic (fcc) and body-centered cubic (bcc) lattices, the primitive lattice vectors are not orthogonal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] However, in these cases the Miller indices are conventionally defined relative to the lattice vectors of the cubic supercell and hence are again simply the Cartesian directions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The defining property of a crystal is its inherent symmetry.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Performing certain symmetry operations on the crystal lattice leaves it unchanged.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] All crystals have translational symmetry in three directions, but some have other symmetry elements as well.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] For example, rotating the crystal 180° about a certain axis may result in an atomic configuration that is identical to the original configuration; the crystal has twofold rotational symmetry about this axis.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In addition to rotational symmetry, a crystal may have symmetry in the form of mirror planes, and also the so-called compound symmetries, which are a combination of translation and rotation or mirror symmetries.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] A full classification of a crystal is achieved when all inherent symmetries of the crystal are identified.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Lattice systems are a grouping of crystal structures according to the point groups of their lattice.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] All crystals fall into one of seven lattice systems.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] They are related to, but not the same as the seven crystal systems.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The most symmetric, the cubic or isometric system, has the symmetry of a cube, that is, it exhibits four threefold rotational axes oriented at 109.5° (the tetrahedral angle) with respect to each other.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] These threefold axes lie along the body diagonals of the cube.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The other six lattice systems, are hexagonal, tetragonal, rhombohedral (often confused with the trigonal crystal system), orthorhombic, monoclinic and triclinic which is the least symmetrical as it possess only identity (E).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Bravais lattices, also referred to as *space lattices*, describe the geometric arrangement of the lattice points, and therefore the translational symmetry of the crystal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The three dimensions of space afford 14 distinct Bravais lattices describing the translational symmetry.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] All crystalline materials recognized today, not including quasicrystals, fit in one of these arrangements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The fourteen three-dimensional lattices, classified by lattice system, are shown above.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The crystal structure consists of the same group of atoms, the *basis*, positioned around each and every lattice point.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] This group of atoms therefore repeats indefinitely in three dimensions according to the arrangement of one of the Bravais lattices.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The characteristic rotation and mirror symmetries of the unit cell is described by its crystallographic point group.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Recent developments in crystallography and intermetallic materials science have led to the identification of a new family of ternary compounds known as ZIP phases.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] These structures are characterised by so-called dualistic atomic ordering, in which different atomic sublattices display distinct ordering behaviour within a single crystal lattice.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] A crystal system is a set of point groups in which the point groups themselves and their corresponding space groups are assigned to a lattice system.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Of the 32 point groups that exist in three dimensions, most are assigned to only one lattice system, in which case the crystal system and lattice system both have the same name.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] However, five point groups are assigned to two lattice systems, rhombohedral and hexagonal, because both lattice systems exhibit threefold rotational symmetry.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] These point groups are assigned to the trigonal crystal system.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In total there are seven crystal systems: triclinic, monoclinic, orthorhombic, tetragonal, trigonal, hexagonal, and cubic.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The crystallographic point group or *crystal class* is the mathematical group comprising the symmetry operations that leave at least one point unmoved and that leave the appearance of the crystal structure unchanged.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Rotation axes (proper and improper), reflection planes, and centers of symmetry are collectively called *symmetry elements*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Each one can be classified into one of the seven crystal systems.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In addition to the operations of the point group, the space group of the crystal structure contains translational symmetry operations.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] By considering the arrangement of atoms relative to each other, their coordination numbers, interatomic distances, types of bonding, etc., it is possible to form a general view of the structures and alternative ways of visualizing them.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The principles involved can be understood by considering the most efficient way of packing together equal-sized spheres and stacking close-packed atomic planes in three dimensions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] For example, if plane A lies beneath plane B, there are two possible ways of placing an additional atom on top of layer B.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The unit cell of a ccp arrangement of atoms is the face-centered cubic (fcc) unit cell.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] This is not immediately obvious, as the closely packed layers are parallel to the {111} planes of the fcc unit cell.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] There are four different orientations of the close-packed layers.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] One important characteristic of a crystalline structure is its atomic packing factor (APF).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] This is calculated by assuming that all the atoms are identical spheres, with a radius large enough that each sphere abuts on the next.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Another important characteristic of a crystalline structure is its coordination number (CN).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] This is the number of nearest neighbours of a central atom in the structure.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The 74% packing efficiency of the FCC and HCP is the maximum density possible in unit cells constructed of spheres of only one size.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Interstitial sites refer to the empty spaces in between the atoms in the crystal lattice.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] These spaces can be filled by oppositely charged ions to form multi-element structures.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] They can also be filled by impurity atoms or self-interstitials to form interstitial defects.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Real crystals feature defects or irregularities in the ideal arrangements described above and it is these defects that critically determine many of the electrical and mechanical properties of real materials.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] When one atom substitutes for one of the principal atomic components within the crystal structure, alteration in the electrical and thermal properties of the material may ensue.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Impurities may also manifest as electron spin impurities in certain materials.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Dislocations in a crystal lattice are line defects that are associated with local stress fields.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Dislocations allow shear at lower stress than that needed for a perfect crystal structure.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The local stress fields result in interactions between the dislocations which then result in strain hardening or cold working.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Grain boundaries are interfaces where crystals of different orientations meet.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] A grain boundary is a single-phase interface, with crystals on each side of the boundary being identical except in orientation.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The term "crystallite boundary" is sometimes, though rarely, used.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Grain boundary areas contain those atoms that have been perturbed from their original lattice sites, dislocations, and impurities that have migrated to the lower energy grain boundary.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Treating a grain boundary geometrically as an interface of a single crystal cut into two parts, one of which is rotated, we see that there are five variables required to define a grain boundary.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The first two numbers come from the unit vector that specifies a rotation axis.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The third number designates the angle of rotation of the grain.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The final two numbers specify the plane of the grain boundary (or a unit vector that is normal to this plane).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Grain boundaries disrupt the motion of dislocations through a material, so reducing crystallite size is a common way to improve strength, as described by the Hall–Petch relationship.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Since grain boundaries are defects in the crystal structure they tend to decrease the electrical and thermal conductivity of the material.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The high interfacial energy and relatively weak bonding in most grain boundaries often makes them preferred sites for the onset of corrosion and for the precipitation of new phases from the solid.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] They are also important to many of the mechanisms of creep.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Grain boundaries are in general only a few nanometers wide.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In common materials, crystallites are large enough that grain boundaries account for a small fraction of the material.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] However, very small grain sizes are achievable.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In nanocrystalline solids, grain boundaries become a significant volume fraction of the material, with profound effects on such properties as diffusion and plasticity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In the limit of small crystallites, as the volume fraction of grain boundaries approaches 100%, the material ceases to have any crystalline character, and thus becomes an amorphous solid.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The difficulty of predicting stable crystal structures based on the knowledge of only the chemical composition has long been a stumbling block on the way to fully computational materials design.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Now, with more powerful algorithms and high-performance computing, structures of medium complexity can be predicted using such approaches as evolutionary algorithms, random sampling, or metadynamics.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The crystal structures of simple ionic solids (e.g., NaCl or table salt) have long been rationalized in terms of Pauling's rules, first set out in 1929 by Linus Pauling, referred to by many since as the "father of the chemical bond".
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Pauling also considered the nature of the interatomic forces in metals, and concluded that about half of the five d-orbitals in the transition metals are involved in bonding, with the remaining nonbonding d-orbitals being responsible for the magnetic properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Pauling was therefore able to correlate the number of d-orbitals in bond formation with the bond length, as well as with many of the physical properties of the substance.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] He subsequently introduced the metallic orbital, an extra orbital necessary to permit uninhibited resonance of valence bonds among various electronic structures.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In the resonating valence bond theory, the factors that determine the choice of one from among alternative crystal structures of a metal or intermetallic compound revolve around the energy of resonance of bonds among interatomic positions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] It is clear that some modes of resonance would make larger contributions (be more mechanically stable than others), and that in particular a simple ratio of number of bonds to number of positions would be exceptional.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The resulting principle is that a special stability is associated with the simplest ratios or "bond numbers": 1⁄2, 1⁄3, 2⁄3, 1⁄4, 3⁄4, etc.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The choice of structure and the value of the axial ratio (which determines the relative bond lengths) are thus a result of the effort of an atom to use its valency in the formation of stable bonds with simple fractional bond numbers.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] This treatment thus emphasized the increasing bond strength as a function of group number.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The operation of directional forces were emphasized in one article on the relation between bond hybrids and the metallic structures.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The resulting correlation between electronic and crystalline structures is summarized by a single parameter, the weight of the d-electrons per hybridized metallic orbital.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The "d-weight" calculates out to 0.5, 0.7 and 0.9 for the fcc, hcp and bcc structures respectively.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The relationship between d-electrons and crystal structure thus becomes apparent.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In crystal structure predictions/simulations, the periodicity is usually applied, since the system is imagined as being unlimited in all directions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Polymorphism is the occurrence of multiple crystalline forms of a material.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] It is found in many crystalline materials including polymers, minerals, and metals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] According to Gibbs' rules of phase equilibria, these unique crystalline phases are dependent on intensive variables such as pressure and temperature.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Polymorphism is related to allotropy, which refers to elemental solids.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The complete morphology of a material is described by polymorphism and other variables such as crystal habit, amorphous fraction or crystallographic defects.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Polymorphs have different stabilities and may spontaneously and irreversibly transform from a metastable form (or thermodynamically unstable form) to the stable form at a particular temperature.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] They also exhibit different melting points, solubilities, and X-ray diffraction patterns.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] One good example of this is the quartz form of silicon dioxide, or SiO2.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In the vast majority of silicates, the Si atom shows tetrahedral coordination by 4 oxygens.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] All but one of the crystalline forms involve tetrahedral {SiO4} units linked together by shared vertices in different arrangements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In different minerals the tetrahedra show different degrees of networking and polymerization.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] For example, they occur singly, joined in pairs, in larger finite clusters including rings, in chains, double chains, sheets, and three-dimensional frameworks.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The minerals are classified into groups based on these structures.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] In each of the 7 thermodynamically stable crystalline forms or polymorphs of crystalline quartz, only 2 out of 4 of each the edges of the {SiO4} tetrahedra are shared with others, yielding the net chemical formula for silica: SiO2.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Another example is elemental tin (Sn), which is malleable near ambient temperatures but is brittle when cooled.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] This change in mechanical properties due to existence of its two major allotropes, α- and β-tin.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] The two allotropes that are encountered at normal pressure and temperature, α-tin and β-tin, are more commonly known as *gray tin* and *white tin* respectively.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Two more allotropes, γ and σ, exist at temperatures above 161 °C and pressures above several GPa.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] White tin is metallic, and is the stable crystalline form at or above room temperature.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Below 13.2 °C, tin exists in the gray form, which has a diamond cubic crystal structure, similar to diamond, silicon or germanium.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Gray tin has no metallic properties at all, is a dull gray powdery material, and has few uses, other than a few specialized semiconductor applications.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Although the α–β transformation temperature of tin is nominally 13.2 °C, impurities (e.g.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Al, Zn, etc.) lower the transition temperature well below 0 °C, and upon addition of Sb or Bi the transformation may not occur at all.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Twenty of the 32 crystal classes are piezoelectric, and crystals belonging to one of these classes (point groups) display piezoelectricity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] All piezoelectric classes lack inversion symmetry.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Any material develops a dielectric polarization when an electric field is applied, but a substance that has such a natural charge separation even in the absence of a field is called a polar material.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Whether or not a material is polar is determined solely by its crystal structure.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Only ten of the 32 point groups are polar.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] All polar crystals are pyroelectric, so the ten polar crystal classes are sometimes referred to as the pyroelectric classes.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] There are a few crystal structures, notably the perovskite structure, which exhibit ferroelectric behavior.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] This is analogous to ferromagnetism, in that, in the absence of an electric field during production, the ferroelectric crystal does not exhibit a polarization.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] Upon the application of an electric field of sufficient magnitude, the crystal becomes permanently polarized.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] This polarization can be reversed by a sufficiently large counter-charge, in the same way that a ferromagnet can be reversed.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/crystal-structure] However, although they are called ferroelectrics, the effect is due to the crystal structure (not the presence of a ferrous metal).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The term "electronegativity" was introduced by Jöns Jacob Berzelius in 1811, though the concept was known before that and was studied by many chemists including Avogadro.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Despite its long history, an accurate scale of electronegativity was not developed until 1932, when Linus Pauling proposed an electronegativity scale that depends on bond energies, as a development of valence bond theory.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] It has been shown to correlate with several other chemical properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Electronegativity cannot be directly measured and must be calculated from other atomic or molecular properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Several methods of calculation have been proposed, and although there may be small differences in the numerical values of electronegativity, all methods show the same periodic trends between elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The most commonly used method of calculation is that originally proposed by Linus Pauling.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] This gives a dimensionless quantity, commonly referred to as the **Pauling scale** (*χ*r), on a relative scale running from 0.79 to 3.98 (hydrogen = 2.20).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] When other methods of calculation are used, it is conventional (although not obligatory) to quote the results on a scale that covers the same range of numerical values: this is known as electronegativity in *Pauling units*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] As it is usually calculated, electronegativity is not a property of an atom alone, but rather a property of an atom in a molecule.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Even so, the electronegativity of an atom is strongly correlated with the first ionization energy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The electronegativity is slightly negatively correlated (for smaller electronegativity values) and rather strongly positively correlated (for most and larger electronegativity values) with the electron affinity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] It is to be expected that the electronegativity of an element will vary with its chemical environment, but it is usually considered to be a transferable property, that is to say, that similar values will be valid in a variety of situations.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] By Pauling scale, caesium is the least electronegative element (0.79); fluorine is the most (3.98).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Pauling first proposed the concept of electronegativity in 1932 to explain why the covalent bond between two different atoms (A–B) is stronger than the average of the A–A and the B–B bonds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] According to valence bond theory, of which Pauling was a notable proponent, this "additional stabilization" of the heteronuclear bond is due to the contribution of ionic canonical forms to the bonding.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] As only differences in electronegativity are defined, it is necessary to choose an arbitrary reference point to construct a scale.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Hydrogen was chosen as the reference, as it forms covalent bonds with a large variety of elements: its electronegativity was fixed first at 0, then in his famous book at 2.1 to avoid negative electronegativity figures, later revised to 2.20 by Allred.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] It is also necessary to decide which of the two elements is the more electronegative (equivalent to choosing one of the two possible signs for the square root).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] This is usually done using "chemical intuition": in the above example, hydrogen bromide dissolves in water to form H+ and Br− ions, so it may be assumed that bromine is more electronegative than hydrogen.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] However, in principle, since the same electronegativities should be obtained for any two bonding compounds, the data are overdetermined, and the signs are unique once a reference point has been fixed (usually, for H or F).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] To calculate Pauling electronegativity for an element, it is necessary to have data on the dissociation energies of at least two types of covalent bonds formed by that element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Allred updated Pauling's original values in 1961 to take account of the greater availability of thermodynamic data, and it is these "revised Pauling" values of the electronegativity that are most often used.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] These are approximate equations but they hold with good accuracy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Pauling obtained the first equation by noting that a bond can be approximately represented as a quantum mechanical superposition of a covalent bond and two ionic bond states.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The covalent energy of a bond is approximately, by quantum mechanical calculations, the geometric mean of the two energies of covalent bonds of the same molecules, and there is additional energy that comes from ionic factors, i.e. polar character of the bond.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The square root of this excess energy, Pauling notes, is approximately additive, and hence one can introduce the electronegativity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Thus, it is these semi-empirical formulas for bond energy that underlie the concept of Pauling electronegativity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The formulas are approximate, but this rough approximation is good and gives the right intuition, with the notion of the polarity of the bond and some theoretical grounding in quantum mechanics.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The electronegativities are then determined to best fit the data.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] In more complex compounds, there is an additional error since electronegativity depends on the molecular environment of an atom.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Also, the energy estimate can be only used for single, not for multiple bonds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The enthalpy of formation of a molecule containing only single bonds can subsequently be estimated based on an electronegativity table, and it depends on the constituents and the sum of squares of differences of electronegativities of all pairs of bonded atoms.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Such a formula for estimating energy typically has a relative error on the order of 10% but can be used to get a rough qualitative idea and understanding of a molecule.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] See also: Electronegativities of the elements (data page) There are no reliable sources for Pm, Eu and Yb other than the range of 1.1–1.2; see Pauling, Linus (1960).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] *The Nature of the Chemical Bond.* 3rd ed., Cornell University Press, p.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] *The Inaccessible Earth: An integrated view to its structure and composition*.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] As this definition is not dependent on an arbitrary relative scale, it has also been termed **absolute electronegativity**, with the units of kilojoules per mole or electronvolts.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] However, it is more usual to use a linear transformation to transform these absolute values into values that resemble the more familiar Pauling values.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The Mulliken electronegativity can only be calculated for an element whose electron affinity is known.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Measured values are available for 72 elements, while approximate values have been estimated or calculated for the remaining elements.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The Mulliken electronegativity of an atom is sometimes said to be the negative of the chemical potential.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Rochow considered that electronegativity should be related to the charge experienced by an electron on the "surface" of an atom: The higher the charge per unit area of atomic surface the greater the tendency of that atom to attract electrons.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The effective nuclear charge, *Z*eff, experienced by valence electrons can be estimated using Slater's rules, while the surface area of an atom in a molecule can be taken to be proportional to the square of the covalent radius, *r*cov.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Sanderson has also noted the relationship between Mulliken electronegativity and atomic size and has proposed a method of calculation based on the reciprocal of the atomic volume.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] With a knowledge of bond lengths, Sanderson's model allows the estimation of bond energies in a wide range of compounds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Sanderson's model has also been used to calculate molecular geometry, *s*-electron energy, NMR spin-spin coupling constants and other parameters for organic compounds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] This work underlies the concept of **electronegativity equalization**, which suggests that electrons distribute themselves around a molecule to minimize or equalize the Mulliken electronegativity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] This behavior is analogous to the equalization of chemical potential in macroscopic thermodynamics.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Perhaps the simplest definition of electronegativity is that of Leland C.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] where *ε*s,p are the one-electron energies of s- and p-electrons in the free atom and *n*s,p are the number of s- and p-electrons in the valence shell.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The one-electron energies can be determined directly from spectroscopic data, and so electronegativities calculated by this method are sometimes referred to as **spectroscopic electronegativities**.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] These energies are obtained by averaging the energies of all spectroscopic terms, weighed according to the S, L and J quantum numbers.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Unfortunately, for the transition metals and the lanthanides the spectroscopic energies of many terms are unknown since their energies overlap or have not been recorded and assigned yet.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Therefore, Allen lists no electronegativities for the lanthanides and employed theoretical methods to estimate the electronegativities of the listed transition metals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The necessary data are available for most of the main group elements, and this method allows the estimation of electronegativities for elements that cannot be treated by the other methods, e.g. francium, which has an Allen electronegativity of 0.67.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] However, it is not clear what should be considered to be valence electrons for the d- and f-block elements, which leads to an ambiguity regarding their electronegativities calculated by the Allen method.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] On this scale, neon has the highest electronegativity of all elements, followed by fluorine, helium, and oxygen.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The wide variety of methods of calculation of electronegativities, which all give results that correlate well with one another, is one indication of the number of chemical properties that might be affected by electronegativity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The most obvious application of electronegativities is in the discussion of bond polarity, for which the concept was introduced by Pauling.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] In general, the greater the difference in electronegativity between two atoms the more polar the bond that will be formed between them, with the atom having the higher electronegativity being at the negative end of the dipole.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Pauling proposed an equation to relate the "ionic character" of a bond to the difference in electronegativity of the two atoms, although this has fallen somewhat into disuse.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] More convincing are the correlations between electronegativity and chemical shifts in NMR spectroscopy or isomer shifts in Mössbauer spectroscopy (see figure).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Both these measurements depend on the s-electron density at the nucleus, and so is a good indication that the different measures of electronegativity describe "the ability of an atom in a molecule to attract electrons to itself".
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] In general, electronegativity increases on passing from left to right along a period and decreases on descending a group.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Hence, fluorine is the most electronegative of the elements (not counting noble gases), whereas caesium is the least electronegative, at least of those elements for which substantial data is available.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] There are some exceptions to this general rule.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Gallium and germanium have higher electronegativities than aluminium and silicon, respectively, because of the d-block contraction.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] In inorganic chemistry, it is common to consider a single value of electronegativity to be valid for most "normal" situations.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] While this approach has the advantage of simplicity, it is clear that the electronegativity of an element is *not* an invariable atomic property and, in particular, increases with the oxidation state of the element.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Allred used the Pauling method to calculate separate electronegativities for different oxidation states of the handful of elements (including tin and lead) for which sufficient data were available.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] However, for most elements, there are not enough different covalent compounds for which bond dissociation energies are known to make this approach feasible.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The chemical effects of this increase in electronegativity can be seen both in the structures of oxides and halides and in the acidity of oxides and oxoacids.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Hence CrO3 and Mn2O7 are acidic oxides with low melting points, while Cr2O3 is amphoteric and Mn2O3 is a completely basic oxide.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The effect can also be seen in the dissociation constants p*K*a of the oxoacids of chlorine.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The effect is much larger than could be explained by the negative charge being shared among a larger number of oxygen atoms, which would lead to a difference in p*K*a of log10(1⁄4) = −0.6 between hypochlorous acid and perchloric acid.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] As the oxidation state of the central chlorine atom increases, more electron density is drawn from the oxygen atoms onto the chlorine, diminishing the partial negative charge of individual oxygen atoms.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] At the same time, the positive partial charge on the hydrogen increases with a higher oxidation state.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] This explains the observed increased acidity with an increasing oxidation state in the oxoacids of chlorine.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The electronegativity of an atom changes depending on the hybridization of the orbital employed in bonding.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Electrons in s orbitals are held more tightly than electrons in p orbitals.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Hence, a bond to an atom that employs an sp*x* hybrid orbital for bonding will be more heavily polarized to that atom when the hybrid orbital has more s character.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] That is, when electronegativities are compared for different hybridization schemes of a given element, the order χ(sp3) < χ(sp2) < χ(sp) holds (the trend should apply to non-integer hybridization indices as well).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] In organic chemistry, electronegativity is associated more with different functional groups than with individual atoms.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] The terms **group electronegativity** and **substituent electronegativity** are used synonymously.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] However, it is common to distinguish between the inductive effect and the resonance effect, which might be described as σ- and π-electronegativities, respectively.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] There are several linear free-energy relationships that have been used to quantify these effects, of which the Hammett equation is the best known.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Kabachnik parameters are group electronegativities for use in organophosphorus chemistry.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Mainly, this is an attribute of metals, meaning that, in general, the greater the metallic character of an element the greater the electropositivity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] Therefore, the alkali metals are the most electropositive of all.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] This is because they have a single electron in their outer shell and, as this is relatively far from the nucleus of the atom, it is easily lost; in other words, these metals have low ionization energies.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] While electronegativity increases along periods in the periodic table and decreases down groups, electropositivity *decreases* along periods (from left to right) and *increases* down groups.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/electronegativity] This means that elements in the upper right of the periodic table of elements (oxygen, sulfur, chlorine, etc.) will have the greatest electronegativity, and those in the lower left (rubidium, caesium, and francium) the greatest electropositivity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] In thermodynamics, the **enthalpy of mixing** (also **heat of mixing** and **excess enthalpy**) is the enthalpy liberated or absorbed from a substance upon mixing.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] When a substance or compound is combined with any other substance or compound, the enthalpy of mixing is the consequence of the new interactions between the two substances or compounds.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] This enthalpy, if released exothermically, can in an extreme case cause an explosion.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] Enthalpy of mixing can often be ignored in calculations for mixtures where other heat terms exist, or in cases where the mixture is ideal.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] The sign convention is the same as for enthalpy of reaction: when the enthalpy of mixing is positive, mixing is endothermic, while negative enthalpy of mixing signifies exothermic mixing.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] In ideal mixtures, the enthalpy of mixing is null.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] In non-ideal mixtures, the thermodynamic activity of each component is different from its concentration by multiplying with the activity coefficient.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] One approximation for calculating the heat of mixing is Flory–Huggins solution theory for polymer solutions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] However, Gibbs free energy of mixing and entropy of mixing tend to be more difficult to determine experimentally.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] As such, enthalpy of mixing tends to be determined experimentally in order to calculate entropy of mixing, rather than the reverse.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] Enthalpy of mixing is defined exclusively for the continuum regime, which excludes molecular-scale effects (However, first-principles calculations have been made for some metal-alloy systems such as Al-Co-Cr or β-Ti).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] When two substances are mixed the resulting enthalpy is not an addition of the pure component enthalpies, unless the substances form an ideal mixture.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] The interactions between each set of molecules determines the final change in enthalpy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] For example, when compound "x" has a strong attractive interaction with compound "y" the resulting enthalpy is exothermic.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] In the case of alcohol and its interactions with a hydrocarbon, the alcohol molecule participates in hydrogen bonding with other alcohol molecules, and these hydrogen bonding interactions are much stronger than alcohol-hydrocarbon interactions, which results in an endothermic heat of mixing.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] Enthalpy of mixing is often determined experimentally using calorimetry.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] A bomb calorimeter is considered to be an isolated system with an insulated frame and a reaction chamber, and is used to transfer the heat of mixing into surrounding water whose temperature is measured.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] A typical solution would use the equation $H_{mixture}=\Delta H_{mix}+\sum x_{i}H_{i}$ (derived from the definition above) in conjunction with experimentally determined total-mixture enthalpies and tabulated pure species enthalpies, the difference being equal to enthalpy of mixing.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] More complex models, such as the Flory-Huggins and UNIFAC models, allow prediction of enthalpies of mixing.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] Flory-Huggins is useful in calculating enthalpies of mixing for polymeric mixtures and considers a system from a multiplicity perspective.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] It can be seen that prediction of enthalpy of mixing is incredibly complex and requires a plethora of system variables to be known.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] This explains why enthalpy of mixing is typically experimentally determined.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] In these equations, the excess and total enthalpies of mixing are equal because the ideal enthalpy of mixing is zero.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] This is not true for the corresponding Gibbs free energies however.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] An ideal mixture is any in which the arithmetic mean (with respect to mole fraction) of the two pure substances is the same as that of the final mixture.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] Among other important thermodynamic simplifications, this means that enthalpy of mixing is zero: $\Delta H_{mix,ideal}=0$ .
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] Any gas that follows the ideal gas law can be assumed to mix ideally, as can hydrocarbons and liquids with similar molecular interactions and properties.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] A regular solution or mixture has a non-zero enthalpy of mixing with an ideal entropy of mixing.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] Under this assumption, $\Delta H_{mix}$ scales linearly with $X_{1}X_{2}$ , and is equivalent to the excess internal energy.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] This method requires that the interactions between two species are unaffected by the addition of the third species. $\Delta H_{ij}$ is then evaluated for a binary concentration ratio equal to the concentration ratio of species *i* to *j* in the ternary mixture ( $x_{i}/x_{j}$ ).
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] Intermolecular forces are the main constituent of changes in the enthalpy of a mixture.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] Stronger attractive forces between the mixed molecules, such as hydrogen-bonding, induced-dipole, and dipole-dipole interactions result in a lower enthalpy of the mixture and a release of heat.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/enthalpy-of-mixing] If strong interactions only exist between like-molecules, such as H-bonds between water in a water-hexane solution, the mixture will have a higher total enthalpy and absorb heat.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] The crystal structures of solute and solvent must be similar.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] Complete solubility occurs when the solvent and solute have the same valency.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] A metal is more likely to dissolve a metal of higher valency, than vice versa.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] The solute and solvent should have similar electronegativity.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] If the electronegativity difference is too great, the metals tend to form intermetallic compounds instead of solid solutions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] Valency factor: two elements should have the same valence.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] The greater the difference in valence between solute and solvent atoms, the lower the solubility.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] Fundamentally, the Hume-Rothery rules are restricted to binary systems that form either substitutional or interstitial solid solutions.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] However, this approach limits assessing advanced alloys which are commonly multicomponent systems.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] Free energy diagrams (or phase diagrams) offer in-depth knowledge of equilibrium restraints in complex systems.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] In essence the Hume-Rothery rules (and Pauling's rules) are based on geometrical restraints.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] Likewise are the advancements being done to the Hume-Rothery rules.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] Where they are being considered as critical contact criterion describable with Voronoi diagrams.
[src:hume-rothery-rules/hume-rothery-rules] This could ease the theoretical phase diagram generation of multicomponent systems.
